There are a number of NaN values in the datasets. This could be attritubed to the unavailibility of data for those years. To make this analysis more meaningful, we'll drop the columns where there are no valid values and interpolate for the years where we don't have data. From the metadata, we see that data is available only if more than 50% of the population is covered, so for any reason the data is not available for a particular year, we can interpolate the data based on its prior and subsequent years data.

Before starting the analysis, it is always good to understand the data, so let us read the metadata and understand what it is, how it is calculated and what some of the assumptions were.

World Bank's library has a neat function that allows you to display metadata within your notebook.

So from the metadata we know the indicator displays % of population for people using atleast basic sanitation services and is collected annually for countries.

Now, let us see what the relative percentage point difference is between the first year the data was collected and the most recent one to understand how % population using basic sanitation has changes over the years.¶

From the above we can see that there are infact a few outliers in the distribution. But what is more interesting is to see the number of countries where % population of people using basic sanitation services from 2000 to 2017 has fallen.

Let's look at the top ten countries with decreasing % population using basic sanitation in a time series plot.¶

The graph above provides us with the differences for data points between the year 2000 and 2018 for the 10 countries with the hightest negative percentage point difference.

Let's now visualize how these numbers are changing over time.¶

The graph above shows the significant decline for countries like Vanuatu, Papua New Guinea and Gambia. But, for other countries the graph shows no significant decline.

Now alternatively, let us now consider top 10 countries with the highest positive difference in percentage points between 2000 and 2018.¶

<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x126c28dd8>

Federated States of Micronesia went up from about 25% in 2000 to over 85% in 2015. This could be the result of major interventions and shift of government's priorities to implement better sanitation facilities in order to minimize the health risks posed by open defecation and unsanitary practices. It also looks like most of these countries belong to low income and lower middle income countries.

Since it is less meaningful to plot all the data for 217 countries on one plot, let us group the data by income and see the temporal change (if any).¶

The results above are somewhat expected. High income countries and upper middle income countries didn't see much change in % population using basic saniation facilities. The numbers have certainly increased for Low-Middle income countries owing to the probable efforts and interventions from a number of international agencies supporting local governments.

Let's first see how world looked for percent population using basic sanitation facilities back in 2000.¶

It is clear from the map that rich countries i.e. high income countries had close to 100% access to sanitation, for instance USA, Canada, Australia and most European countries. Whereas poorer countries in South Asia and Africa had poor access to these services (attributing to lighter color on the map).

Now's lets see how this indicator changed in 2017.¶

Compared to its predecessor, this map shows better use of sanitation services worldwide. It would be interesting to map more accurately the change that has happened in last two decades for more keen observation.

Below is the map depicting the difference in percentage points for sanitation services used by % population between 2000 and 2017 to help analyze the same.¶

It is interesting to see that countries like Cambodia, FSM, Nepal and India has highest % point change between the two years. As mentioned earlier, this could be because of change in priorities or change in population relative to the services although the latter seems unlikely. It is also interesting to look at the the countries with the majority of percentage point difference has been in the 2nd quintile (-7.93 points to 4.72 points) and the 3rd quintile (16.36 points to 33.86 points). This shows that a majority of the countries experienced only a nominal percentage point change despite a span of 20 years having passed. It is also interesting to see that a majority of the High income countries belonging to the second quintile. Though this makes sense, since these countries had very high to perfect sanitation scores in 2000 itself thereby portraying negligble change.

Discussion¶

The data under consideration, gives the percent population having access to basic sanitation facilities that include flush/pour flush to piped sewer systems, septic tanks or pit latrines; ventilated improved pit latrines, compositing toilets or pit latrines with slabs. From figure 6 and figure 7 we can visually see the changes where these numbers have either increased or decreased. Access to sanitation is an important development indicator; poor sanitation can cause serious health issues thereby having cascading effects on a country's economy. Low income and low middle income country governments often don't have enough budget to build sophisticated medical infrastructure, and hence their best bet is to usually start from the ground up and work in areas where they can minimize the dramatic effects of illnesses. Having proper sanitation facilities at home can help avoid the transmission of diseases such as cholera, diarrhea, dysentery, hepatitis A, typhoid and polio and exacerbates stunting.[Source]

In 2017, about 73.4\% of global population had access to basic sanitation facilities, an increase from 55.46\% in 2000 [goto]. The maximum change over this period of two decades can be seen in South Asia and other low middle income countries [goto]. Countries are classified as low income if the Gross National Income (GNI) per capita is less than \$1,025 low middle income if GNI per capita is between \\$1,026 and \$3,995 respectively[[Source]](https://datahelpdesk.worldbank.org/knowledgebase/articles/906519-world-bank-country-and-lending-groups). With over [20 countries](https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GNP.PCAP.CD?most_recent_value_desc=false) countries having GNI per capita less than \\$1000, it makes it very challenging for the government to create proper programs for sanitation. For instance, poor sanitation costs Malawi (one of the lower ranking countries in GNI per capita list) about US $57 million for factors ranging from premature deaths to costs of healthcare, which in turn has cascading effects on country's economy.

India on the other hand went from 16\% in 2000 to about 60\% in 2017, an increase of 44\% point. New government implemented sanitation programs like Total Sanitation Campaign in 1999, Nirmal Bharat Abhiyan in 2012 and Swachh Bharat Mission in 2014 have helped curb the open defecation issues in rural parts of India. These efforts also encourage the use of communal toilets in urban slums that is otherwise reponsible for major health hazard outbreaks. There have been multiple studies where lack of sanitation services have been linked with women safety. In one the studies, authors identified health impacts of open defecation, increased risk of secxual exploitation, threat to women's privacy and psychosocial stressors linked to open defecation.

In conclusion, the numbers show how far we've come to tackle the issue of sanitation and how local governments and international agencies are working in harmony to to eradicate the concept of open defecation. The issue of sanitation can be tied to multiple sustainable development goals such as health issue (SDG Goal 3), gender issue (SDG Goal 5) and sanitation issue (SDG Goal 6). With better and more accurate data at disposal, the policy makers can act efficiently and make actionable decisions.
